Exercise 1

The default bar chart is hard to read because the labels on the x-axis are squished together. We can fix this by flipping the coordinates, as described in the diamonds chapter. (This is just one way to solve the prolbem. Students can use other way to solve it, such as rotating the x-axis labels 45 degree.)

ggplot(gss_cat, aes(rincome)) + geom_bar() + coord_flip()

Exercise 3

In this dataset, denom only applies to Protestants. To get this information in a table, use a group_by.

gss_cat %>% group_by(relig) %>% summarise(denoms=n_distinct(denom)) %>% arrange(-denoms)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

##    relig                   denoms
##    <fct>                    <int>
##  1 Protestant                  29
##  2 Christian                    4
##  3 Other                        2
##  4 No answer                    1
##  5 Don't know                   1
##  6 Inter-nondenominational      1
##  7 Native american              1
##  8 Orthodox-christian           1
##  9 Moslem/islam                 1
## 10 Other eastern                1
## 11 Hinduism                     1
## 12 Buddhism                     1
## 13 None                         1
## 14 Jewish                       1
## 15 Catholic                     1

We see that Protestant, Christian, and Other have denominations. One way to see this visually is a heatmap. (This is just one way. Students can use other plot to show the findings as long as it is reasonable.)

ggplot(gss_cat, aes(x=relig, y=denom)) + geom_tile()

Chapter 15 (15.5.1 Exercises)

Exercise 1

Ill use a plot to show how the proportions have changed over time.

gss_cat %>% mutate(partyid = fct_collapse(partyid,
                                         other = c("No answer", "Don't know", "Other party"),
                                        rep = c("Strong republican", "Not str republican"),
                                        ind = c("Ind,near rep", "Independent", "Ind,near dem"),
                                        dem = c("Not str democrat", "Strong democrat")
                                        )
                   ) %>% 
    group_by(year, partyid) %>%
    count() %>% 
    group_by(year) %>% 
    mutate(prop=n/sum(n)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=year, y=prop, fill=partyid)) + geom_area()

The proportions have been more or less stable since 2000. The number of Republicans has shrank slightly, with some of that loss being taken up by independents.

Exercise 2

We can use fct_lump to collapse rincome into a smaller set of categories (e.g.5 categories.)

gss_cat %>% mutate(rincome=fct_lump(rincome, n=5)) %>% count(rincome)
